Immediate Super Eagles’ manager  Gernot Rohr is on the verge  of clinching a lucrative contract with another  African  side  barely  weeks after he was unceremoniously  ditched by the  Nigeria Football Federation(NFF)  on the eve of the  recently concluded  Africa Cup of Nations  (AFCON) Cameroon 2021.  There have been several  coaching openings  post AFCON as federations review performances with both Ghana  and Tunisia already parting ways  with Milovan Rajevac  and Mondher Kebaier respectively Though  Rohr had earlier hinted  that he won’t  be heading to  Ghana  since the West African side  would be facing off  against Nigeria  for one of the continent’s  five tickets to the  Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup, the  68-year-old  German  has  exclusively revealed to NationSport  that he  is now  seriously  studying  three coaching offers , adding  he  recently turned down an offer to tinker with French Lique 1 side Bordeaux. “ I’m in touch with three countries actually  and even the club of Bordeaux wanted me to come over  and save the team from relegation but  I don’t want (Bordeaux),” Rohr told NationSport  but refrained from naming the three interested countries.“ But very soon, I will take my decision  where I want to go.”   Philip lauds Obaseki over equal pay for Insurance, Edo…     Club World Cup: Chelsea  stop Ighalo’s  Al- Hilal     Qatar 2022 race : Ghana picks Addo ,Hughton  for Eagles   Meanwhile, Rohr  has equally explained that he still has unfinished business with the NFF  over the vexed contractual  disagreement  after he was fired days to the kick-off of the AFCON. - Advertisement - A confidant of the  former Bayern Munich defender  had queried  the rationale  behind  the decision of the  NFF  to pay part of his outstanding wages into a domestic  account consequently  the recourse  to drag  the issue before the  world’s soccer ruling body, FIFA.  “ Of course, there is no news  yet (from FIFA) with the problem with the NFF  but as you know, I still have a contract  till the end of the year  as well as with the unpaid bonuses and allowances,”  Rohr further told NationSport.“ I will still fight for my stuffs  but the lawyers  are still working on it.”